---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="About the River Tamar - Drip Drip Tamar">
  <main class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-8">
    <header class="mb-8">
      <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-gray-900 mb-4">
        The River Tamar
      </h1>
      <p class="text-lg text-gray-600">
        Understanding Cornwall and Devon's border river
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
      <section class="mb-8">
        <div class="card">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">River Overview</h2>
          <p>
            The River Tamar forms the historic boundary between Cornwall and Devon, flowing for 61 miles 
            (98km) from its source on the north Cornwall moors to its estuary at Plymouth Sound.
          </p>
          
          <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mt-6">
            <div>
              <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Key Facts</h3>
              <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-600">
                <li><strong>Length:</strong> 61 miles (98 km)</li>
                <li><strong>Source:</strong> Woolley Moor, near Bude</li>
                <li><strong>Mouth:</strong> Plymouth Sound</li>
                <li><strong>Catchment area:</strong> 917 kmÂ²</li>
                <li><strong>Counties:</strong> Cornwall & Devon</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div>
              <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Major Towns</h3>
              <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-600">
                <li>Launceston</li>
                <li>Calstock</li>
                <li>Gunnislake</li>
                <li>Saltash</li>
                <li>Plymouth (estuary)</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="mb-8">
        <div class="card">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Water Quality Challenges</h2>
          
          <div class="space-y-4">
            <div>
              <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Agricultural Runoff</h3>
              <p class="text-gray-600">
                The Tamar catchment is predominantly rural with extensive farming. Rainfall can wash 
                nutrients and bacteria from agricultural land into the river, particularly affecting 
                water quality after heavy rainfall events.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div>
              <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Sewage Infrastructure</h3>
              <p class="text-gray-600">
                Like many UK rivers, the Tamar receives treated sewage effluent and can be affected 
                by combined sewer overflows during intense rainfall when treatment systems become overwhelmed.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div>
              <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Tidal Influence</h3>
              <p class="text-gray-600">
                The lower Tamar is tidal up to Gunnislake weir. Tidal action can transport pollution 
                upstream and concentrate contaminants, making water quality highly variable in the 
                tidal reaches.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div>
              <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Seasonal Variation</h3>
              <p class="text-gray-600">
                Water quality varies significantly with seasons. Winter storms increase runoff and 
                bacterial contamination, while summer low flows can concentrate pollutants but also 
                reduce dilution of point sources.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="mb-8">
        <div class="card">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Our Monitoring Sites</h2>
          
          <div class="space-y-6">
            <div>
              <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Okel Tor (Upper Tamar)</h3>
              <p class="text-gray-600 mb-2">
                Located in the upper catchment near Launceston, this site represents freshwater 
                conditions before significant urban and industrial influences. Water quality here 
                is primarily affected by agricultural runoff and natural background sources.
              </p>
              <div class="text-sm text-gray-500">
                <span class="chip">Freshwater</span>
                <span class="chip">Agricultural catchment</span>
                <span class="chip">Upper river</span>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div>
              <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Calstock (Lower Tamar)</h3>
              <p class="text-gray-600 mb-2">
                Situated in the tidal reach, this site experiences the combined effects of upstream 
                pollution, tidal mixing, and additional inputs from the lower catchment. Results 
                here reflect the cumulative water quality of the entire river system.
              </p>
              <div class="text-sm text-gray-500">
                <span class="chip">Tidal</span>
                <span class="chip">Estuarine</span>
                <span class="chip">Lower river</span>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="mb-8">
        <div class="card">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Recreational Activities</h2>
          
          <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">
            The River Tamar supports various recreational activities, each with different 
            water quality considerations:
          </p>

          <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
            <div>
              <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Water Contact Activities</h3>
              <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-600">
                <li>Swimming</li>
                <li>Kayaking & Canoeing</li>
                <li>Paddleboarding</li>
                <li>Wild swimming</li>
              </ul>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mt-2">
                These activities have higher exposure risk and require attention to bacterial levels.
              </p>
            </div>
            
            <div>
              <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Lower Contact Activities</h3>
              <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-600">
                <li>Fishing</li>
                <li>Boating</li>
                <li>Walking riverside paths</li>
                <li>Wildlife watching</li>
              </ul>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mt-2">
                Lower risk activities but still worth checking conditions.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section>
        <div class="bg-green-50 border border-green-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">
            Protecting the Tamar
          </h3>
          <p class="text-green-800 mb-4">
            Everyone can help protect water quality in the River Tamar. Simple actions like 
            properly disposing of waste, using eco-friendly products, and reporting pollution 
            incidents all make a difference.
          </p>
          <div class="flex gap-4">
            <a href="/contact/" class="btn bg-green-600 text-white hover:bg-green-700">
              Report Issues
            </a>
            <a href="/about/" class="btn bg-green-200 text-green-800 hover:bg-green-300">
              Learn More
            </a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>
    </div>
  </main>
</Layout>